Path: godot/tutorials/animation/playing_videos.rst
Summary: This section explains how to handle resizing and aspect ratios for VideoStreamPlayer nodes using AspectRatioContainer.
By default, the VideoStreamPlayer will automatically be resized to match the video's resolution. You can make it follow usual Control sizing by enabling Expand on the VideoStreamPlayer node.

To adjust how the VideoStreamPlayer node resizes depending on window size, adjust the anchors using the Layout menu at the top of the 2D editor viewport. However, this setup may not be powerful enough to handle all use cases, such as playing fullscreen videos without distorting the video (but with empty space on the edges instead). For more control, you can use an AspectRatioContainer node, which is designed to handle this kind of use case:

Add an AspectRatioContainer node. Make sure it is not a child of any other container node. Select the AspectRatioContainer node, then set its Layout at the top of the 2D editor to Full Rect. Set Ratio in the AspectRatioContainer node to match your video's aspect ratio. You can use math formulas in the inspector to help yourself. Remember to make one of the operands a float. Otherwise, the division's result will always be an integer.

Once you've configured the AspectRatioContainer, reparent your VideoStreamPlayer node to be a child of the AspectRatioContainer node. Make sure Expand is enabled on the VideoStreamPlayer. Your video should now scale automatically to fit the whole screen while avoiding distortion.

See doc_multiple_resolutions for more tips on supporting multiple aspect ratios in your project.
---CHUNK---
Document: Playing Videos
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/playing_videos.rst
Summary: This section explains how to display a video on a 3D surface in Godot using a SubViewport and a VideoStreamPlayer.

To display a video on a 3D surface, you can use a VideoStreamPlayer node as a child of a SubViewport node. This allows any 2D node, including video, to be rendered onto a 3D surface. This technique is useful for creating animated billboards without consuming excessive memory for frame-by-frame animations.

The process involves these steps:

1.  Add a SubViewport node to your scene. Configure its size to match the resolution of your video.
2.  As a child of the SubViewport, add a VideoStreamPlayer node. Assign your video file to its stream property. Ensure the "Expand" property is unchecked. Enable "Autoplay" if you want the video to start playing automatically.
3.  Create a MeshInstance3D node. Assign a PlaneMesh or QuadMesh to its Mesh property. Adjust the mesh's dimensions to match the video's aspect ratio to prevent distortion.
4.  In the GeometryInstance3D section of the MeshInstance3D, set the Material Override property to a new StandardMaterial3D resource.
5.  Within the StandardMaterial3D's Resource section (at the bottom), enable "Local To Scene". This is a mandatory step before you can assign a ViewportTexture to the Albedo Texture property.
6.  In the StandardMaterial3D, navigate to the Albedo section and set the Texture property to a new ViewportTexture. Click on the newly created ViewportTexture resource to edit it. In its properties, set the Viewport Path to your SubViewport node.
7.  To ensure accurate color representation and prevent washed-out colors, enable "Albedo Texture Force sRGB" in the StandardMaterial3D.
8.  If the 3D object displaying the video needs to act as a light source, set the Shading Mode to "Unshaded" in the StandardMaterial3D. This can also improve rendering performance.

For further details on viewports and practical examples, refer to the documentation on viewports and the "GUI in 3D" demo project.
---CHUNK---
